paragraphs.text: A slang way to say ‘My mistake’ when you realize you’ve made a minor error
Oops, I spilled some water. My bad, I’ll clean it up. [audio:phrases_verbs_my_bad_2]
Oh, is that your Coke? My bad, I thought it was mine. [audio:phrases_verbs_my_bad_3]
When used in a dating context, it means to arrange a date or meeting between two people who are single
My sister set us up, and we had a great first date! [audio:phrases_verbs_set_someone_up_2]
Luke: No, but my friends keep trying to set me up with people they know.
(link xx) See more uses of ‘Set up’
In the context of dating apps, to ‘match’ with someone means that you and another user ‘liked’ or ‘swiped right’ on each other
I matched with my cute neighbor. I hope he messages me! [audio:phrases_verbs_match_2]
Ooh! I matched with three new people today. [audio:phrases_verbs_match_3]
This is used to refer to someone who has many positive qualities as a romantic partner, like kind, successful, attractive, smart, etc
Sarah's new boyfriend is a real catch - he's smart, funny, and he has a great job. [audio:phrases_verbs_a_catch_2]
You should go on a date with Libby. She’s definitely a catch. [audio:phrases_verbs_a_catch_3]
I think my girlfriend is going to break up with me. [audio:phrases_verbs_break_up_2]
Sally and Drew broke up a few months ago, but they’re still good friends. [audio:phrases_verbs_break_up_3]
Wow, I can’t believe he said that. That’s so rude. [audio:phrases_verbs_wow1_2]
To place an item on a surface for storage or display
Did I put my keys on the table? [audio:phrases_verbs_put_on_2]
I put a plate of cookies on the counter. [audio:phrases_verbs_put_on_3]
(link xx) See more uses of ‘Put on’
Stop standing around and get to work! We have a lot to clean. [audio:phrases_verbs_get_to_work_2]
Okay, I should get to work. My project is due this Friday. [audio:phrases_verbs_get_to_work_3]
To try to improve, achieve, or finish something
I’m trying to work on my Thai pronunciation. [audio:phrases_verbs_work_on_2]
I’m working on my science project right now. [audio:phrases_verbs_work_on_3]
To visit someone at their home
Do you want to come over for dinner after work? [audio:phrases_verbs_come_over_2]
Sorry I can’t come over today, I’m feeling a bit sick. [audio:phrases_verbs_come_over_3]
I need to go through these documents before the meeting. [audio:phrases_verbs_go_through_2]
The customs officer had to go through all of my luggage before I could board my flight. [audio:phrases_verbs_go_through_3]
A sound made to show surprise and sympathy
Luke: My grandma’s really sick right now. [audio:phrases_verbs_aww1_2]
Pailin: Aww, I’m sorry to hear that.
To not bother or disturb someone or thing
I don’t like to leave my dog alone at the house for too long. [audio:phrases_verbs_leave_alone_2]
Leave your brother alone. He’s trying to sleep. [audio:phrases_verbs_leave_alone_3]
To make a short visit somewhere
Could you stop by the store on your way home from work? We need more eggs. [audio:phrases_verbs_stop_by_2]
I stopped by my ex’s house yesterday to pick up my things. [audio:phrases_verbs_stop_by_3]
My grandparents came to the US a long time ago. [audio:phrases_verbs_a_long_time_ago_2]
That restaurant was popular a long time ago, but it’s so dead these days. [audio:phrases_verbs_a_long_time_ago_3]
A phrase said to show you expect something must be true
Pailin: My brother just flew in from Thailand. He must be exhausted. [audio:phrases_verbs_i_bet_2]
Luke: I bet! That’s a super long flight.
Pailin: Ethan can’t wait to quit his job. [audio:phrases_verbs_i_bet_3]
Luke: I bet! His boss sounds like a horrible person.
